# Sprint Workflow

## When Implementing a Sprint

1. Read the sprint file thoroughly -- follow tasks in order
2. Check the **Depends On** field to ensure prerequisite sprints are complete
3. Reference the linked feature files and docs for detailed requirements
4. Follow acceptance criteria as the definition of done
5. Check off tasks as you complete them

## Sprint File References

- `sprints/roadmap.md` -- overview, dependency graph, feature-to-sprint mapping
- `features/` -- detailed feature specs with user stories, requirements, and open questions
- `docs/architecture/backend.md` -- DB schema, API endpoints, project structure
- `docs/architecture/frontend.md` -- Next.js structure, routing, state, canvas layers
- `docs/design/design-system.md` -- theme, colors, component styling
- `docs/design/screen-layouts.md` -- wireframes, UX flows, keyboard shortcuts
- `docs/testing-strategy.md` -- test stack, conventions, per-sprint testing expectations

## Key Conventions

- Each sprint builds on previous ones -- always verify dependencies first
- The event_log table should capture all data changes from Sprint 01 onward
- RLS policies must be added to every new table
- All new API endpoints need JWT auth middleware and org_id scoping
- Test with the acceptance criteria checklist before marking a sprint complete

## Testing Requirements

- Every feature PR must include unit + integration tests
- Backend: pytest tests in `tests/unit/` and `tests/integration/`
- Frontend: Vitest tests colocated or in `__tests__/`
- Coverage must not drop below 80% (enforced by CI)
- E2E tests (Playwright) are written during Sprint 15, not per-feature
- Mock external services (Supabase, Liveblocks, DodoPayments) at the boundary
- See `docs/testing-strategy.md` for full conventions and test file structure
